               <msContents>
                  <summary>I) Daily Office Prayers and Litanies (fols. 5ra-23ra)
 II) Śǝrʿāta
                     qǝddāse “Ordinary of the Mass” (fols. 23va-52ra), preceded by disciplinary
                     regulation concerning clergy (fol. 23rb-va)
 III) Anaphoras (fols.
                     52rb-147rb)
 III-1) Anaphora of the Apostles (fols. 52rb-64vb)
 III-2)
                     Anaphora of Our Lord Jesus Christ (fols. 65ra-79ra)
 III-3) Anaphora of St
                     John Son of Thunder (fols. 79ra-88ra)
 III-4) Anaphora of the 318 Orthodox
                     Fathers of Nicaea (fols. 88ra-95vb)
 III-5) Anaphora of St John Chrysostom
                     (fols. 96ra-101rb)
 III-6) Anaphora of St Epiphanius of Cyprus (fols.
                     101va-107ra)
 III-7) Anaphora of St Dioscorus of Alexandria (fols.
                     107rb-110rb)
 III-8) Anaphora of St Jacob of Serug (fols. 110rb-116rb)
                     III-9) Anaphora of St Gregory (“Hosanna-liturgy of St Gregory”) (fols.
                     116rb-122rb)
 III-10) Anaphora of St Basil of Caesarea (fols.
                     122va-130vb)
 III-11) Anaphora of St Athanasius of Alexandria (fols.
                     131ra-141ra)
 III-12) Anaphora of St Cyril of Alexandria (fols.
                     141rb-147rb)
 III) Ṣalota ʿǝṭān “The Prayer of Incense”, followed by a
                     prayer (fols. 147rb-156vb)
 
 Additiones 1-3.</summary>
                  <msItem xml:id="ms_i1">

                     <incipit>
                        <foreign xml:lang="en"/>
                     </incipit>
                     <explicit>
                        <foreign xml:lang="en"/>
                     </explicit>
                     <note/>
                  </msItem>
                  
                  <msItem xml:id="ms_i2">
                     <note>In the incipit of the Anaphora of St John Chrysostom (<locus target="#96ra">96ra</locus>) the author of the Anaphora is mistakenly
                        named “John, patriarch of the city of Alexandria”.</note>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
